cs.HC, cs.IR, cs.SI, cs.CL, cs.CY 

This paper deals with analyzing large-scale click data from Wikipedia to understand what makes a link successful. The study involves analyzing the effects of link properties on the popularity of links, user preferences towards links leading to the periphery of the network, semantically similar articles, and links in the top and left-side of the screen. The paper also integrates these findings into a navigational Markov chain model and adapts and improves the classic PageRank algorithm. Based on these aspects, the most likely sub-category is Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC), followed by Information Retrieval (cs.IR), Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Computational Linguistics (cs.CL), and finally, Computers and Society (cs.CY).
